{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "The concepts of work and play have become farcically reversed: schoolwork is meant to be superfun and play, like homework, is meant to teach.", "abstract": "Dispatch column by Pamela Paul observes that concepts of work and play with respect to education of children have become reversed; notes schoolwork now is meant to be fun, while play, in form of video games, is designed to be educational; suggests allowing children to play games that are not educational in their free time and tasking them with schoolwork that is challenging.", "section_name": "Sunday Review", "print_page": "4", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Pamela", "role": "reported", "lastname": "PAUL", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By PAMELA PAUL", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/17/sunday-review/reading-writing-and-video-games.html", "lead_paragraph": "The concepts of work and play have become farcically reversed: schoolwork is meant to be superfun and play, like homework, is meant to teach.", "headline": {"seo": "Reading, Writing and Video Games", "main": "Reading, Writing and Video Games", "print_headline": "Reading, Writing and Video Games", "content_kicker": "Dispatch", "kicker": "Dispatch"}, "_id": "51470d1efdc5926e77000129", "word_count": "1059", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2013/03/17/sunday-review/17GALAGA/17GALAGA-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2013/03/17/sunday-review/17GALAGA/17GALAGA-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 699, "url": "images/2013/03/17/sunday-review/17GALAGA/17GALAGA-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2013/03/17/sunday-review/17GALAGA/17GALAGA-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "699"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2013/03/17/sunday-review/17GALAGA/17GALAGA-thumbSta